Strategy Performance

Unfortunately, our strategy significantly underperforms the S&P 500 in the backtest period (01/2011-01/2013). When the strategy is first implemented, it outperforms the benchmark, but by the end of 2011, the S&P 500 is back to superior returns. We believe this is due to our pairs selection algorithm, which chose cointegrated and correlated periods from 2006-2010. We would like to create an algorithm in which pairs are reselected each year based on the past four years of data, as we believe this will allow our portfolio to outperform the S&P 500 consistently. Overall, this was a successful strategy throughout our backtest period, with annual returns of 5.1% and total returns of 10.4%. Our portfolio does not exhibit exceptional volatility, and as a result has a nice Sharpe ratio of 0.89. The maximum drawdown during this period is not significantly poor at -4.8%.

Additionally, we observe a daily value-at-risk of -0.7%, implying that 5% of days, we will observe losses in excess of this. The volatility in our portfolio (as shown in the Rolling Volatility plot) is significantly lower than that of our benchmark, making our portfolio appear to be a safer investment. Our portfolio also performed well during stress events in this period. During the US Downgrade/European Debt Crisis, we outperformed the benchmark in returns. We also observe superior returns during the EZB IR Event. Our largest position was in Cardinal Health at 14.39%, which is a reasonable weight placed on one asset, allowing for increased diversification across multiple assets. Relative to returns attributable to common risk factors, our portfolio performed very well, with 6.32% annualized return specific to our strategy. So while there are a few improvements that could be made, this appears to be a good foundation for an extremely successful pairs trading strategy.

Ability to Hit Goals and Constraints

We meet structural requirements for Quantopian. While our strategy does not utilize the Optimize API, our systematic pairs are selected from within the Quantopian Tradable Universe. We trade on the following pairs: Pelangio Exploration & BHP Group, Centurylink & DISH Network, Honda Motor Co & Disney, Clorox & Molson Coors Brewing Co, Imperial Oil & Total SA, American Express & American International Group, Aethon Minerals & Cardinal Health, Automatic Data Processing & Cummins, Equity Residential & Brookfield Asset Management, Cerner Corporation & Apple, and PG&E Company & Enterprise GP Holdings.

We meet the requirement for sector exposure, with low exposure to a wide range of sectors, with no more than 0.01 average exposure to each of the 11 sectors. However, we did not meet the requirement for style exposures, with significant exposure to size and short-term reversal across our backtest. This is due to the fact that we choose pairs from the top 10 stocks in each sector, leading to extreme size exposure. It makes sense that we have exposure to short-term reversal strategy, as that is the very nature of pairs trading. We long the asset that is performing poorly and short the asset that is performing better, fully expecting a reversal of performance.

Our strategy fails to meet the leverage requirement of staying between 0.8 and 1.1x leverage. Some days, we have leverage in excess of the 1.1x maximum, and some days, we hold cash which puts us below the 0.8x minimum. And although our backtest does not acknowledge it due to the lag in our strategy that has us holding cash until July 2011, we meet the the turnover rate requirement (between 5 and 65% daily average turnover). We also meet the constraint of market beta less than 0.3, showing low correlation to the market. Unfortunately, our portfolio had some position concentration in excess of the maximum limit of 5% required, which could be fixed through a maximum asset weighting constraint. We also failed to meet the net dollar exposure of no more than 10% difference between long and short positions. This, like the previous constraint, could be remedied by the inclusion of maximum asset weighting constraints in our strategy.

Possible Enhancements

One possible enhancement would be to our selection of cointegrated and correlated pairs. Because we chose assets from the top 10 assets in each sector, we had significant exposure to the size factor. We may want to include assets that are not specifically the top assets in a sector in order to better diversify. Additionally, we understand that correlation is not constant across all periods, and recognize that pairs should be reselected on a regular base to account for this. Ideally, we would update pairs once a year using data from the previous four years.
